  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "78:40-55. Let not those that receive mercy from God, be thereby made bold to sin, for the mercies they receive will hasten its punishment; yet let not those who are under Divine rebukes for sin, be discouraged from repentance. The Holy One of Israel will do what is most for his own glory, and what is most for their good. Their forgetting former favours, led them to limit God for the future. God made his own people to go forth like sheep; and guided them in the wilderness, as a shepherd his flock, with all care and tenderness. Thus the true Joshua, even Jesus, brings his church out of the wilderness; but no earthly Canaan, no worldly advantages, should make us forget that the church is in the wilderness while in this world, and that there remaineth a far more glorious rest for the people of God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And he brought them to the border of his sanctuary - The Septuagint and the Latin Vulgate render this, \"to the mountain of his holiness\"; that is, his holy mountain. But the reference is rather to the whole land of Canaan. He brought them to the borders of that land - the land of promise - the holy land. They who came out from Egypt did not indeed enter that land, except Caleb and Joshua, but they were conveyed to its borders before all of them fell. It was true also that the people - the Hebrew people - came to the promised land, and secured its possession.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Even to this mountain - Mount Zion, for the object of the psalm was to show that the worship of God was properly celebrated there. See Psalm 78:68. The meaning is not that the people who came out of Egypt actually inherited that mountain, but that their descendants - the people of God - had been put in possession of it.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Even to this mountain - Mount Zion, for the object of the psalm was to show that the worship of God was properly celebrated there. See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 78:68",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The meaning is not that the people who came out of Egypt actually inherited that mountain, but that their descendants - the people of God - had been put in possession of it.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which his right hand had purchased - Had procured, or obtained possession of. That is, he had secured it by his power. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Which his right hand had purchased - Had procured, or obtained possession of. That is, he had secured it by his power. ",
            "children": []
          },
